com.tsgrp.migration.event.source.listener

Class PdfParserAttributeSetterListener

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.tsgrp.migration.event.AbstractListener
      • com.tsgrp.migration.event.source.listener.PdfParserAttributeSetterListener
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    SourceEndExportNodeEventListener

    public class PdfParserAttributeSetterListener
extends AbstractListener
implements SourceEndExportNodeEventListener
    This listener reads the content from a PDF (your file must be a PDF) and sets properties based on regex information. The tricky part is understanding the required regexAttrMap variable: - Map < String, List > - The key of the map is the name of the attribute that will be populated (ex. om_source_id) - The value of the map is a list of Strings, a list of regex patterns that will be used to match a value in the PDF's text through iText. It will set that value as onto the attribute defined as the key for this map. ONLY THE FIRST SUCCESSFUL match will be set onto the attribute. Because only the first value is selected, this only works for single value field attributes in OM.

      • setRegexAttrMap

        public void setRegexAttrMap(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.util.List<java.lang.String>> regexAttrMap)
        Injected, REQUIRED. Map of attributes (key) and list of regex patterns to find a value for that attribute on the PDF text. IMPORTANT: Each regex pattern MUST have a capture group, as only the first capture group in a single regex pattern will be used to extract the value for the attribute.

      • getFirstPageText

        protected java.lang.String getFirstPageText(MigrationNode node)
        Gets the content from the node and extracts the content of the first page in the form of a PDF document. It then uses iText to get the text of the first page of a document, and set it to a usable String object. ASSUMPTION: Content of Migration Node is a PDF.
        Parameters:
        node - - A Migration node, who's content is assumed to be a PDF document.
        Returns:
        A string with entire text of the document's first page. Returns a blank string if first page text isn't found.
